  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Humanitarian and Prevention  WASH  assistance for Vulnerable Residents in Abu Hujar Locality - Sennar State</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The project targeted ten villages with its catchment areas including Alsabonabi, Seiro, Alrgiba, Aboul, Taybat Elbahar, Galgni, Umkhirien, Albugaa, Allieuna and Mushirat in Abu Hujar locality &#x2013; Sinnar state with estimated population 55700 (13101 boys, 14192 girls, 13635 men amp 14772 women) individuals. The project will increase access to safe drinking water through rehabilitation, upgrading, and improvement of community water sources including water yards and hand pups, in addition to water connection and installation of storage facilities in health care facilities and schools, this will be accompanied with water quality monitoring including treatment and testing for drinking water. The project will also work to ensure availability of appropriate sanitation facilities in health care facilities and schools through construction of new latrines /and or rehabilitation of existing toilets, and ensure availability of hand washing facilities near to toilets and in visible designated areas in health facilities and schools to encourage people to practice and promote hand washing, this in addition to construction of medical waste disposal (incinerator) facilities each health facility to ensure proper management of solid and medical waste. The project will build the capacity and resilience of targeted communities to cope with disaster while raising their awareness to fight current COVID-19 outbreak, promote hygiene among targeted communities through delivering of key hygiene massages using appropriate mechanism. The project proposed to support cleaning and solid waste management activities in schools, health care facilities and at community level through provision of essential cleaning tools, materials and disinfectants to ensure proper infection, prevention and control measures at health facilities and schools, incentives for hygiene promotors and sanitation workers (latrines attendance) will be provided.</narrative>
  </description>
